Please see [`BeanDefinitionRegistryPostProcessor.postProcessBeanDefinitionRegistry()` method][1] javadocs. This is *exactly* what you are in need of, because it lets you modify Spring&#39;s application context **after normal bean definitions have been loaded** *but* **before any single bean has been instantiated**.

    @Configuration
